The paper deals with the analysis of two classic variants of the Traveling Salesman Problem using the toolkit of fine-grained complexity. The first variant is the Bitonic TSP problem, which involves finding a shortest tour consisting of two monotone chains. This problem is related to computational geometry and algorithms, which suggests that cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is a likely sub-category. The second variant is the $k$-OPT heuristic for TSP in the graph setting, which involves finding an improved tour by replacing $k$ edges in the tour by $k$ new edges. This problem is related to algorithms and optimization, which suggests that cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.CC (Computational Complexity), cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics), and cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) are likely sub-categories.
